<subSubSection id="C365ADC6FFB4FFD846E0FB57FB24536C" pageId="4" pageNumber="405" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC0FE4DFFB4FFD846E0FB57FB24536C" blockId="4.[166,1225,1161,1328]" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">
R e m a r k: male specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7F85CEFFB4FFD84401FB56FD3B529A" authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1873" box="[570,682,1197,1223]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Oxycera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="405" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="notata">
<emphasis id="B90B225FFFB4FFD84401FB56FD3B529A" box="[570,682,1197,1223]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">O. notata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has tarsi completely yellow (
<figureCitation id="1344E2C8FFB4FFD8423AFB57FBD1529B" box="[1025,1088,1196,1223]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[181,214,1782,1804]" captionTargetBox="[307,1095,905,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-245@3.[307,1099,883,1762]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Oxycera fallenii: female lateral view (a); Oxycera meigenii: male dorsal view (b), female dorsal view (c); Oxycera notata: male dorsal view (d), female lateral view (e), Oxycera trilineata: female dorsal view (f)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6449252" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6449252/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">fig. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B90B225FFFB4FFD84277FB57FBCA529A" box="[1100,1115,1196,1222]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">d</emphasis>
), but the original description of this species indicated that they have the last two or three tarsal segments darkened that is assumed to be a variable character. Fore tarsus of a female is entirely black and mid and hind tarsi yellow but last two tarsal segments are black (
<figureCitation id="1344E2C8FFB4FFD8426CFAEEFB02536C" box="[1111,1171,1301,1328]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[181,214,1782,1804]" captionTargetBox="[307,1095,905,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-245@3.[307,1099,883,1762]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Oxycera fallenii: female lateral view (a); Oxycera meigenii: male dorsal view (b), female dorsal view (c); Oxycera notata: male dorsal view (d), female lateral view (e), Oxycera trilineata: female dorsal view (f)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6449252" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6449252/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">fig. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B90B225FFFB4FFD842A4FAEDFB3A5373" box="[1183,1195,1302,1327]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">e</emphasis>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
